{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \S2, fourth-best from your longest suit — a normal start against the diamond game.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] You are in 5\D needing eleven tricks. Your trumps are strong and the hearts will set up, but the hand's engine is dummy's \CA-Q-J-6-5-2 opposite your SINGLETON. Six clubs facing one: ask yourself what that suit can be made to produce, what stands in its way, and what it will cost to clear the obstacle. Plan before you play.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] West led the \S2 to East's jack. Get to dummy and cash the \CA — your singleton goes — then lead the \CJ and let it run: East covers with the KING, and you simply RUFF it away. Dummy's queen and the little clubs behind her are now established winners for your heart losers. Draw trumps, concede the \HA, and eleven tricks are there.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] That was the RUFFING FINESSE: a long broken sequence facing shortness, so the honors run through the defender — ruff the cover, or pitch on the duck; either way the suit never loses a trick. The same play that carried the Ruffing Finesse lesson, here dressed in a minor-suit game. Well spotted.}
