{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \H8. With a singleton heart in hand, leading it is natural against a suit contract — it sets up a possible ruff and is the standout choice here.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] You are in 4\S needing ten tricks. There is a club position you could finesse, and after three boards of hooks it may be tempting on reflex. Stop. Count your winners first — trumps, aces, the diamond pair — and then decide: does this hand need a finesse at all, and what could taking one cost you?

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] West led the \H8, which looks very much like a singleton — a ruff is brewing. Win the \HA and draw ALL the trumps immediately to kill it. Now count: five trumps, the \HA, \DA-K, and \CA make ten before any finesse enters the conversation. So take none: never lead toward the \CJ, because losing that trick puts East in to cash the hearts he holds in strength. Draw, cash, claim.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] The exam's first trap: a finesse was AVAILABLE, and the correct number of finesses to take was ZERO. Counting showed ten tricks on top, so the club hook offered nothing and risked the one thing that could hurt you — East on lead with hearts. To Finesse or Not: count first, and the best finesse is often the one you decline.}
