{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \DA. Partner opened diamonds, and cashing your ace while looking at dummy is the natural start against the jump to game.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] East opened 1\D and you shot out 4\H on your eight-card suit — ten tricks needed. The trump suit is \HK-J-9-8-6-5-3-2 facing a singleton, missing the ACE and the QUEEN. The ace is a trick you can never avoid. The queen is the exam question: with only five hearts out there, how do you play the suit — and does the auction whisper anything about where the missing cards sit?

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] West cashed the \DA and shifted; ruff your diamond loser early if they persist. When trumps are led toward your hand, do not bang the king: insert the JACK. West's ace takes it — a trick the defense always owned — but look what happened to East's queen: it fell in the wash, dead under your king on the next round. East opened the bidding, so the outstanding honors were marked over dummy; the jack-insert played for exactly that. Draw the rest and use the spade finesse position for your black-suit tricks: ten in all.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] The finesse into the bidder, from the To Finesse or Not lesson — and in the TRUMP suit, the exam's favorite hiding place. You could never dodge the ace, but the queen was always East's on the auction, and the jack-insert made her worthless. Listen first, then finesse.}
