{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \HK, top of your \HK-Q-T sequence — the standard attack against the spade game.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] You are in 4\S needing ten tricks. Trumps will behave, but count the diamonds: dummy's A-T-7-4 opposite your Q-6-2, missing the KING and the JACK together. One diamond trick is certain; the game wants THREE. Two honors are out against you — remember the arithmetic from the Double Finesse lesson: when two cards are missing, you get two chances, and you are allowed to lose to one of them. Plan how the suit must be played, and from which side.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] West cashes hearts and gets out; win, draw trumps. Diamonds now: take dummy's ACE, return to dummy, and lead TOWARD your queen — East's king climbs on empty air, capturing nothing. Your queen stands. And when East's jack appears on the next round, the queen swallows it and dummy's TEN is suddenly a winner too. Three diamond tricks from Q-6-2 and A-T-7-4, losing only what was always theirs: ten tricks home.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] Two missing honors, two chances — the double-finesse arithmetic in work clothes. You led toward your broken honors twice; the king could only beat air, the jack fell to the queen, and the ten collected the dividend. Count the missing honors before you play the suit: two out means two ways to win.}
