{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \HA, top of your \HA-K — take your tricks and a look at dummy while you decide.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] You are in 4\S after West's takeout double, needing ten tricks. The diamond suit is the crux: dummy's A-K-J-6-3 opposite your T-7-2, missing the queen — and this is a TWO-WAY position. Dummy's jack traps her if she sits with West; your ten traps her if she sits with East. You cannot try both. Before touching the suit, replay the auction in your mind: somebody at this table promised opening values, and somebody else promised nothing at all.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] West cashes the top hearts and shifts; win and start trumps — East's king will score, that was always his. The diamond decision: West DOUBLED, so the missing high cards — the queen included — sit over there. Play him for her: lead low toward dummy and insert the JACK. It holds. Cash the king (she does not drop — three to the queen, as it happens), and at the last her queen falls under dummy's ace. No guess: the double had already testified.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] The two-way finesse from the lesson, resolved the grown-up way: not by coin flip but by listening. West's takeout double marked the queen, the jack-side hook was the only one you ever considered, and the queen was dead the moment the auction ended. When both hooks are available, the bidding usually casts the deciding vote.}
