{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \CA, top of your eight-card suit — cash it and look at dummy before choosing what comes next.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] West threw in a 4\C overcall — EIGHT clubs, as it turns out — and you bought the hand in 4\S, needing ten tricks. Your diamond holding is the exam's last temptation: A-Q-J-6 over dummy's 9-4-3-2, a finesse position straight off the first page of the textbook. Before you take it, do what this family taught you first and always: COUNT WEST'S HAND. Eight clubs leaves him five cards for three suits. What does that do to the odds — and to the geometry?

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] West cashes the \CA and East even ruffs the second club — the shape is confirmed: West began with eight clubs and almost nothing else. Draw trumps — West's QUEEN drops singleton, the first warning shot. Now diamonds, and do NOT finesse: with five non-club cards, West's king — if he has it — is singleton or void, and he sits BEHIND your queen-jack, where a stiff king eats a finesse whole. Cash the ACE — and down comes the king, alone. Your queen and jack rule the suit: ten tricks.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] The cast-iron finesse was the losing play — the stiff king behind your tenace would have captured the queen, and the drop was free the whole time. That is Rabbi's Rule exactly as the lesson taught it: not a superstition, a COUNT. Eight clubs on your left made the king short; the ace asked no questions. The prettier the finesse looks, the harder you should count before taking it.}
