{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \S6, fourth-best from your longest suit — the standard start against 3NT.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] You are in 3NT needing nine tricks, and no single suit gets you there. TWO suits offer extra tricks: the diamonds, where your ace-nine sits over dummy's jack-ten-eight, and the clubs, where dummy's queen and your ace-jack-ten surround the missing honors. The exam question is not "which finesse wins" — it is "in what ORDER do you take your chances, so that if the first fails, the second is still standing?"

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] Win the spade in hand and test the diamonds first: the eight forces East's queen, your ace takes it, and the second round goes to West's KING — chance one has failed. No matter: it failed EARLY, while everything else was still under control, and dummy's jack is now a winner. On to chance two: lead dummy's club QUEEN and let it ride — East ducks, it holds. Continue the jack, then the ace; East's king never scores. The clubs deliver three tricks, the ninth is home, and the hand never depended on any one card.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] Choice of Finesses, the combining lesson: two 50-50 chances taken in the right order are three chances in four. The diamond chance died and it did not matter, because you had spent it FIRST, cheaply, while the club chance was still intact. Take your chances in the order that keeps the survivor alive — the deepest habit on the whole finesse shelf.}
