[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \S9, top of your small spades — the safe choice against the slam with nothing attractive anywhere.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] You are in 6\H after EAST opened the bidding — remember that; it is the only clue you get. Trumps are strong, spades run, clubs disappear on a void. Everything narrows to diamonds: your \DA-J-9-3 opposite T-4-2, missing the king AND queen, and you can afford exactly ONE loser there. Where are those honors, and how do you play the suit so the dangerous one never scores?

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] Spades come first — win, draw trumps. Diamonds now, with the auction in your ear: East opened, so play East for the KING. Lead low from dummy and insert the NINE. West wins the QUEEN — the one diamond trick you had to lose — but the position has snapped shut: East's king is trapped, and when the suit comes back, your ace-jack sits over it. The king is picked up, twelve tricks, slam made.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] Evidence first, then a deep finesse: the nine lost to the queen, and that was FINE — it was East's marked king that could never be allowed to score, and it never did. You spent the loser you could afford to trap the honor you could not. That is finesse play at the slam table: the auction told you which opponent to play for what.}
